1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"–":"Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1450–1482":"1450–1482","1401–Male":"1401–Afdød","1401":"1401","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"–":"Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1450–1482":"1450–1482","1401–Male":"1401–Overleden","1401":"1401","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1450–1482":"1450–1482","1401–Male":"1401–Deceased","1401":"1401","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Alstan</i>, which is a coalescence of several different Old English personal names: <i>Æthelstān</i> ‘noble stone’, <i>Ælfstān</i> ‘elf stone’, <i>Ealdstān</i> ‘old stone’, or <i>Ealhstān</i> ‘temple stone’.","habitational name from any of various places called Alston (in Cumbria, Lancashire, Devon, and Somerset) or Alstone (in Gloucestershire and Staffordshire). With the exception of Alston in Cumbria, which is formed with the Old Norse personal name <i>Halfdan</i>, these placenames all consist of an Old English personal name + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, for example <i>Ælfsige</i> in the case of Alstone in Gloucestershire."],"variants":[{"name":"Aston","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Ad(e)stan</i>, which is usually from Old English <i>Æthelstān</i> (see   Alston  ). It may also be from the much rarer Old English name <i>Ēadstān</i>.","habitational name from any of several places in England called Aston. Most were named with Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. In a few cases the first element is <i>æsc</i> ‘ash tree’."]},{"name":"Allston","meanings":["English: variant of   Alston  ."]},{"name":"Hailstone","meanings":["habitational name from Hailstone Hill in Wiltshire or Hailstone Farm in Gloucestershire, the former of which may be derived from Old English <i>hālig-stān</i> ‘holy stone’ or <i>hagolstān</i> ‘hailstone’ (Middle English <i>hawelston</i>, <i>hailston</i>).","from <i>Ailstan</i>, a variant of the Old English personal name <i>Æthelstān</i> (‘noble’ + ‘stone’), with prosthetic initial <i>H-</i>. The first element of the Old English name developed from <i>Æthel-</i> to <i>Ægel-</i> and then to <i>Ail-</i>; it was often further shortened to <i>Al-</i> (see   Alston  ).","English:"]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Alston was born as the son of John Alston. He had at least 1 daughter with Joane Standolffe."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1450–1482":"1450–1482","1401–Male":"1401–Surnud","1401":"1401","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1450–1482":"1450–1482","1401–Male":"1401–Kuollut","1401":"1401","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1450–1482":"1450–1482","1401–Male":"1401–Décédé","1401":"1401","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert Alston est né, fils de John Alston. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Joane Standolffe."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","–Male":"Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1450–1482":"1450–1482","1401–Male":"1401–Verstorben","1401":"1401","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Robert Alston wurde, als Sohn von John Alston geboren. Er hatte mit Joane Standolffe mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"–":"Desede","–Male":"Desede","–Female":"Desede","1450–1482":"1450–1482","1401–Male":"1401–Desede","1401":"1401","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Angletè, United Kingdom"},"hu":{"–":"elhunyt","–Male":"elhunyt","–Female":"elhunyt","1450–1482":"1450–1482","1401–Male":"1401–elhunyt","1401":"1401","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, Anglia, United Kingdom"},"id":{"–":"Telah Meninggal","–Male":"TelahMeninggal","–Female":"Telah Meninggal","1450–1482":"1450–1482","1401–Male":"1401–Telah Meninggal","1401":"1401","1450":"1450","1482":"1482","Alston Hall, Worcester, Worcesters